A team of four Nevada FFA members placed 6th and earned a gold award at the 2020 Iowa FFA Livestock Evaluation Contest. The event was held Saturday, August 29th at the Hanson Center on the campus of Iowa State University.

Carson Mather was 7th place overall high scoring individual. Other team members were Ellie Moser, Chloe Henry, and Marshal Sheldahl. The FFA Livestock Evaluation Career Development Event provides an opportunity for FFA members to display their agricultural knowledge and skills in the area of Livestock Evaluation. Activities included placing breeding and market classes of beef, swine, sheep and goats; keep/cull and oral reasons classes; and a general knowledge test.

#NevadaCubPride #NevadaHighSchool

If the ticketing system does not work for you, please pass questions to Brian Petersen (R-S AD) by e-mail bpetersen@roland-story.k12.ia.us.

post_text:
NHS & NMS Fans:

Please note that the HOIAC Conference has passed two regulations that will take effect at all NCSD events during fall activities (HOME & AWAY):

1. Masks required in commons areas (While Entering, at Concessions & at Restrooms).

During NCSD Activities Events (home & away) a mask is required in common areas (entering the facility, purchasing concessions & using the restroom). Masks are not required while seated as a spectator. Social distancing and alternate row seating should be followed. Please make sure you bring a mask with you to all conference events.

If you forget your mask, you will be able to purchase a mask at the entry gate for $1. All Varsity level contests will be live-streamed and can be watched from the comfort of your home.

2. Children & students in K-8th grade must be accompanied by a parent or adult during all events.

This includes at entry, during the event, while using concessions & restrooms.

Thank you for your support and understanding with following these rules & regulations so we can provide our students with fall activities.

NEW THIS YEAR you will also be asked if you wish to choose on-site learning (with safety measures in place), or online learning from home through NCSD.

Returning Families: Register Here --> https://nevada.powerschool.com/public/
New Families: email registration@nevadacubs.org to get started

post_text:
We want to celebrate our 'Last Day Of School' with our families! Mark your calendars for the 'Summer Send-Off' Teacher Parade!

Wednesday 6/3, 6-7pm

Hop in your vehicle and drive through our parade route so our Nevada staff can wish you one final 'goodbye' as we wrap up the 2019-20 school year. Teachers & Staff will line up along the sidewalks of their particular buildings and wave to you as you drive past!

Below is the route for drivers.

1. Enter on J Ave - West of Central Elementary School
2. Turn South on 10th St
3. Turn East on H Ave
4. Turn North on 15th St
5. Exit onto Lincoln Hwy

Please drive slowly and remain in your vehicles.

*Safety personnel will be placed at specific intersections*

COVID-19 Update - Summer Sports

On Wednesday, May 21st, Governor Reynolds announced that the high school baseball and softball seasons would be allowed this summer, beginning June 1. We know that many of you have questions as to how this will look for Nevada and what precautions and accommodations will be necessary for our athletes, coaches, and spectators. Please know that our administration is actively working through a myriad of state and federal guidance documents on this topic.

READ MORE --> https://www.nevadacubs.org/2020/04/covid-19-updates/

post_text:
Happy Earth Day and Arbor Day! Tomorrow, Friday, April 24th, was supposed to be Central's annual tree planting project. Although we are unable to complete the project this year, we want to join together as a community and celebrate the Earth and our wonderful town!

Please join us in wearing your 'Helping Our Community Grow' t-shirt OR any green shirt to celebrate the 60 new trees the Central students have planted the past 2 years! Share a picture on your Facebook page of you and your family wearing green and doing something to help the Earth tomorrow! You could pick up trash, plant beautiful flowers or vegetables, recycle cans and bottles, or just enjoy the outdoors!

We appreciate your support and look forward to bringing more new life to our community in the Spring of 2021!

While the District is closed in response to COVID-19, we are committed to continuing to support your students' learning. The District offers a number of ways for students to engage in learning while they are away from school.

The activities below will not take the place of regular classroom instruction but will supplement student learning at home. These activities are not required or graded. There are both online and offline options - you do not need a computer or the internet to do many of them. Additionally, there is information under the Parent Resources tab for ways to talk with your children about the current COVID-19 situation.

These activities are meant to provide optional opportunities for student learning and enrichment while they are away from school. Like any other time throughout the year, we encourage families to continue student learning at home.

The District will continue to add resources to this page throughout the closure.

https://sites.google.com/view/ncsddigital/home

COVID-19 Update 3/15/20

Tonight, Governor Reynolds announced that she is recommending that Iowa school districts close for four weeks to mitigate the spread of COVID-19.

Nevada Community School District will follow the advice and cancel all programs, activities, and classes effective March 17, 2020. This includes outside organizations who access our buildings including Nevada Community Resource Center (NCRC).

The Nevada Community School District is on a scheduled Spring Break this upcoming week, March 16 - 20. We will keep you updated as we find out more information that will help you plan for the coming weeks.

https://www.nevadacubs.org/2020/03/covid-19-update-3-15-20/

January 24 at 5:55 PM ·

We are taking registrations for preschool and kindergarten for the 2020-21 school year. If you have a child, or know of one, who will be four years old by Sept. 15th, 2020, please call Central Elementary to get your child signed up for our 4 yr. Old Preschool Program.

If you have or know of a child who will be five years old by Sept. 15th, 2020, please call Central Elementary to register for Kindergarten. You do NOT need to call if your child is currently attending preschool here.

The Nevada School Board recently reviewed a comprehensive facility assessment for Nevada Middle School. The assessment was completed by Estes Construction via a partnership provided by the Iowa Association of School Boards. The assessment summary estimated the cost of renovations to be in the range of $5,320,750 to $7,693,236 depending on the scope of work decided by the School Board. Nearly half of the projected cost is targeted at new roofing and new heating/cooling systems, confirming those areas the District had previously identified as top facility concerns. [ 58 more words ]

post_text:
Ten Nevada FFA members and FFA advisor Kevin Cooper attended the Iowa FFA Legislative Symposium held on Tuesday, January 28th. Students started with a large group meeting of over 700 FFA members from across the state at the Embassy Suites Downtown Des Moines location.

Undersecretary of Ag Julie Kenney addressed the students on the current status of agriculture in Iowa, and the opportunities which available. Kelsey Tyrell, director of World Food Prize Youth Institutes, also provided information to the students on how to advocate for agriculture and communicate to legislatures.

Representative Dave Deyoe met with the students and placed great emphasis on how being in FFA helped him develop as a young person. Deyoe went on to explain the legislative processes. Students then toured the legislative library and took the stairs to the top of the rotunda.

Kelsey Tyrell, director of World Food Prize Youth Institutes, also provided information to the students on how to advocate for agriculture and communicate to legislatures.

Representative Dave Deyoe met with the students and placed great emphasis on how being in FFA helped him develop as a young person. Deyoe went on to explain the legislative processes. Students then toured the legislative library and took the stairs to the top of the rotunda.

Nevada Community School District is excited to announce that Tony Sneiderman has been named principal of Nevada Middle School starting this upcoming fall. Sneiderman came to Nevada with past experience as an Activities Director and business teacher. [ 26 more words ]

Harmony Clothing Closet and Nevada High School have teamed up to provide storage space for the nonprofit, while giving students valuable hands-on experience. A handful of students in industrial tech teacher Greg Baethke’s high school woodworking class have been building shoe racks for Harmony Clothing Closet, after a request came from fellow school staff member Elizabeth Gindt. Harmony Clothing Closet is a nonprofit clothing pantry that gives away clothes and household items to people in need. [ 444 more words ]
https://www.nevadacubs.org/2020/01/harmony-clothing-closet-get-custom-storage-nevada-shop-students/
